{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945090701/1011.xml":{"full_text":"Page Four\nTOLEDO UN5ON JOURNAL\nOfficial Publication\nToledo Industrial Union Council\nORGANIZETOLEDO 100%\nPublished every Eridav by Local No. 12\nLAW CIO.. 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo. Ohio\nMember of Amenoui Labor Pre** Association\nEditor .........................Melvin Schults\nManaging Editor O. J. Pecord\nAdvertising Manager Burn Zawodny\nBoard of Trustees\nMelvin Schultz, Thomas Burke,\nRandolph Grav\nSUBSCK1PT1ON RATES\nOne year, by mail. In advance ..,.$1.5$\nEntered at the Toledo. Ohio, post office\nsecond class matter under tile act of\nAug. 24, 1912.\nCritical Problems\nAs Congress meets this week, it faces\nproblems of peace no less critical than the\nproblems which were created by the Japs\nsneak attack on Pearl Harbor. The Japs\npeace attack caught us just as flat-footed\nas their initial sneak military blow.\nWhen the Japs brought the war to us,\nCongress was in Washington. Quickly, in\nfact, the very next day, the representa\ntives of the people met to hear President\nRoosevelt's narration of the \u201cday that will\nlive in infamy\u201d and it responded by\nimmediately declaring war on the aggres\nsor.\nWhen the Japs brought sudden peace\nto us, Congress was fishing, or taking\njunkets to Europe at governmental ex\npense, or building political fences back\nhome. Nobody got excited, least of all\nour congressional representatives. Ob\nviously, it makes a difference who is at\ntacked and who does the attacking.\nIn 1941, there were several million\nunemployed in this country. War require\nments demanded full production, and full\nproduction demanded men and women\nand even young boys and girls to meet\nthe need. Laws protecting female and\nchild lahor were set aside for the dura\ntion and American Lahor put its shoulder\nto the wheel in a great national effort to\nbring defeat to the enemies of the coun\ntry.\nAnd so today we stand, a nation which\nhas achieved military victory in the\nworld\u2019s bloodiest and most destructive\nwar waiting for our Congress to inaugu\nrate the beginning of the campaign to win\nthe peace.\nToday, whether Congress realizes It or\nnot, the future peace of the world rests\nin its hands, for more than any other fac\ntor which exists in the world today, upon\nthe treatment of the American working\nclass depends the future peace and wel\nfare of the world.\nFull employment is not unattainable\nin peacetime. What can be done for war\nand death and destruction, cad* and must\nbe done for peace and prosperity. No\nother course is open to us. We must make\nour choice.\nLabor has made its choice. It is for\npeace and prosperity through full employ\nment and adequate social security for all.\nLabor\u2019s position is clear. It demands the\nsame full employment and adequate liv\ning wages, in time of peace which was\ngrudgingly given it of necessity in time of\nwar.\nCongress, that great, stupid, slow mov*\ning body composed largely of second rate\nstatesmen, pernicious politicians and frus\ntrated lawyers, must rise above itself and\nperform as it has never performed before,\nit must recognize that it is not kicking\naround narrow^ {sectional political ques\ntions, but issues which involve the peace\nand future welfare of the entire world.\nFull employment, increased unem\nployment compensation and adequate so\ncial security benefits for all are not\ngifts to labor, hut the rights of every man,\nwoman and child in this country to live as\nbefits their dignity as human beings, with\na fair stake in the resources of the coun\ntry which they transform into usable\nwealth.\nLabor has no illusions about the pres*\nent Congress. It is not overly optimistic\nnor unduly pessimistic. It recognizes that\nthe political minds in the two great poli\ntical parties remain about the same today\nas they were before the war. They only\nsee what is close to them, regarding a\nmilitary attack of an enemy with fear,\nlinger end military retaliation, but su\n-pinely and indifferently standing hy\nWhile unemployment grows and people\nUse up their dwindling resources in a\ntain struggle against unemployment and\nits tragic result*.\nCongress can do one of two things.\nEither it can stall, and compromise, and\nsow the seeds of newer and bigger emer\ngencies, or it can recognize the situation\nfor what it is\u2014part of the continued crisis\nof an economic system which cries for\nfree enterprise and profits without giving\nthe workers of hand and brain their fair\nshare in the products of their toil.\nThe end of the struggle did not see\nthe. end of the international economic\ncrisis, but merely a change in its condi*\ntion. Congress must meet that challenge\nVr face the consequences.\nThere is no road back to grandfather**\nW5som. We have to deal with the world as it\nW The only way is forward. We are out in the\ndarkling plain in this fateful year of 1945. We\n\u00aeve lost a great leader, and an ominous jour\nney lies before us. There is no escape to an\neconomic fairyland where invisible hands put\nus to bed and rock us to sleep. We have only\nour naked intelligence to save us from loom\ning disaster. We have got to stand on our feet\nand act and dare\u2014yes, and plan! Or mankind\nwill be overwhelmed.\u201d\n\u2014Stuart Chase, Economist.\n4\nWhat\u2019s\nNew?\nBy\nEdward Duck\nWith Th\u00ab\n45th Infantry\nin Germany\nTOMORROW\nSignificant are these words\nWhich the late Franklin De\nlano Roosevelt left us just the\nday before his passing away.\nOn April 11, 1945, his message\nWas: \u201cThe only limit to the\nRealization of tomorrow will\nbe our doubts of today. Let\nUs move forward with strong\nand active faith.\u201d\nHad he known that he was\nsoon to die, he could not have\nChosen a simpler or more ap\npropriate thought, nor ex\npressed himself better. Quite\nsome time before this he had\ntold his people that they had\nhelped throughout his twelve\nyears as their leader, that the\njob was theirs, that they had\nthe \u201cgreen light,,\u201d and that\nthey should not be discou\nraged by skeptic*, defeatists,\nor reactionaries.\nThe man who never made\na mistake never accomplished\nanything worthwhile. The per\nson to be shunned is not the\none who makes an honest mis\ntake, but rather he who is\nafraid to take a step in the\ndirection of progress for fear\nhe will fail, or for fear that\nhis critics will call him an\nidealist, a dreamer, or an opti\nmist.\nIf the war was fought\nfor the so-called \"realists,\u201d\nWho could more properly be\ncalled reactionaries, it was a\ncruel and inhuman butchery\ncontest. If international car\ntel agreements embracing\nmany of the industries vital\nto the war production poten\ntial of Germany and Japan\nare allowed to continue, it\nwill indeed be a mockery of\nthe sacrifices the American\npeople have made.\nNOT IN VAIN\n\u201cWe here highly resolve\nthat these dead shall not have\ndied in vain,\u201d stated Lincoln\nin all sincerity in his memor\nable address at Gettysburg.\nThese words are in stark con\ntrast to what is taking place\nin the United States Congress\ntoday. We had to wait eighty\nyears to discover that Ameri\nca was not entirely free, that\nthe slaves had been only par\ntially freed, and that white\nslaves had joined their ranks.\nThe guilty parties in such\nshameful actions call therms\nselves \u201crealists,\" no doubt.\nThose who are making an\nhonest effort to see that right\nprevails over might, and hon\nesty and sincerity over fraud\nand deceit are branded \u201cvi\nsionaries.\u201d\nWhat our President was try\ning to tell us in these words is\nthat we have a fight on our\nhands, that in order to achieve\nsomething worthw i 1 e we\nmust work for it, that we musk\nbelieve in ourselves, and rid\nour ranks of those who say \"It\ncan\u2019t be done.\u201d\nSocial security, the forty\nhour week with proper over\ntime, unemployment insur\nance, government housing pro\njects and home loan agencies,\nand rural electrification were\nbut a few of the things which\n\"couldn\u2019t bo done,\u201d which\nidealists and visionaries, but\ncertainly not realists nor eco\nnomists, dreamed up in their\nidle moments.\nHOLLOW BUBBLE\nThe wonderful, beautiful,\nUtopian postwar world of\nwhich we have heard so much\nwill be a hollow bubble if\nleft to the realists of the all\npowerful clique known as\norganized management. We\nhave seen their handiwork be\nfore, and their spokesmen are\nworking overtime today, steal\ning the picture from the real\nplanners. Their is no \"fear\u201d\nin their ranks, lest it be fear\nthat the public might wake up\nto their scheme of establishing\ncomplete industrial dictator\nship while waving the Ame\nrican flag and patriotically\ncalling their scheme the \"Ame\nrican way of life.\"\nIf these worthy gentlemen\nwanted a real American way\nOf life they would be setting\ntip machinery for establish\nment of a national wage scale\nwith similar pay for similar\nwork. They would be reading\npostwar readjustments in fe\nmale and child labor laws.\nThey would be demanding\nmore safey precautions for\nminers, and scoring the poll\ntaxers and aaU-FEPQ un\nAmericans.\nTomorrow will be a lovely\nday if the people unite be\nhind real loaders, and if they\nand their leaders substitute\nfaith for doubt, optimism for\npessimism, and progressive\nness for conservatism. The\npwbXcju belongs to all of us.\nin\n'll\nIt\u2019s News\nTo Me...\nI\nBy\nO. J.\nPecord\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nI There are two schools of thought with Respect to the full\n(employment program advocated by labor.\nI On the one hand, labor says that if full employment can be\n(attained in time of war, it must be possible in time of peace. It\n(further says that there can be no peace without full employment!\n(and security.\nBusiness and industry, and you can include the bankers, say\n(that full employment is a mirage beautiful to look at, but unat\ntainable in a system which talks about, but never quite reaches\n(\"free enterprise.\u201d\nAnd so, we have the conflict of ideas, the conflict of actual\nity in which labor constantly seeks but never attains its goal,\n(while capitalistic enterprise pays lip service to a freedom and\n(ideal which at never has, and never will attain.\nI THE FACTS\nIn order to arrive at some general notion of the prospects\n|for full employment in a system which is torn with conflicting\n(ideologies, we must view the past, the immediate past of wartime\n(production, and base our expectations of the future upon tti*\n(only thing we have to pass judgment.\nWe have just completed the greatest war in history. The re\n|cent conflict was a mechanized war in which all the ingenuity\n|of man was put to full test. Mechanical warfare plus chemical\n(warfare such as the world has never before known, has left us\ntoo stupified and amazed to realize the implications which World\nWar II means to the present and the future world.\nMechanical warfare demands men and machines. It mean*\n(that Instead of man becoming the slave of the machine, the ma\u00ab_\n(chine becomes the servant of man, for in war, the machine is\n(victorious and the men who create the victorious machines\n(go along for the ride. True, death comes to millions of men, bul\n|in the end, the machine must be controlled by man after na\npkins are beaten into abject and unconditionay surrender.\nIn time of mechanized warfare, there is no unemployment,\n(instead, there is a definite manpower shortage, for the test of\n(strength lies not only in men, but, more importantly, in outpro\nducing the enemy in the instruments of death and destruction.\n(Thus, job's outnumber the available manpower regardless which\n(nation wins the war.\n(peace\nis different\nPeace is different. No longer is there any need to outpro\nduce the enemy, for the enemy no longer exists. He has been\n(robbed of his ability to wage war indeed, he is very probably\n(prevented from even competing in the peacetime rivalry which\n(exists in a world of industrialized nations. And with this return\n|to peacetime production we come face to face with the theory\n|of capitalistic endeavor to \u201cpurchase on the cheapest market and\n(sell on the dearest.\"\nSince industry purchases labor the same as it does any other\n(commodity, it is only reasonable to expect that it will attempt to\n(follow the same practices with respect to labor, which it uses in\n(buying other materials. And it does. Moreover, it seeks by\n(methods which are sometimes devious to bring about conditions\n(which will force down the price of labor.\nOne of the conditions which industry seeks to impose upon\n(labor in order to control its price is unemployment. Thus, even\nin normal times, there are several millions unemployed, a so\n|called \u201cnormal float\u201d of workless people who bid down jobs in\n(order to secure work. When the unemployed become very\n(numerous, the bidding for jobs becomes more animated\n|and as a result, there is a very gratifying decrease (to industry)\nin the price of labor.\nIsiTPLY AND DEMAND\nAs a commodity, labor seems to respond to the law of sup\nply and demand almost similar to any of the other material\n(used by the industrialists. The more plentiful the supply of la\n|tor, the cheaper it becomes. The scarcer labor becomes, Ute\nli igher its price.\nIndustrialists love a surplus of labor. Labor has an intense\n(dislike for unemployment. The former finds that it is easier to\n(control the price of labor and thus may amass, at least tempor\n(arily, greater profits, while the workers discover that they do\n|not earn sufficient to purchase back a sufficiently large enough\n(volumn of the goods it produces.\nWhen this occurs, layoffs ^ake place and continue until\n|surh a time that the industrialists are able to work off their sur\nplus of manufactured goods, either by selling to foreign nations,\n|or by slowly ridding themselves of their products.\nI LABOR KNOWS\nLabor is well aware of the economic philosophy of the in\n(dustrialists. It recognizes that it must bring about full employ\n|ment or find itself a drug on the market, and in the realization\nI of these economic facts, it reaches for the weapons which are at\nI hand to combat the evils which rob it of work and security.\nI Political action is the course American labor has picked as\nits means of seeking to overcome the advantage which is held\nover it by those who own and control the means of producing\nthe wealth of the country. Ballots rather than bullets are the\nweapons which American workers use to bring upon a more\nequitable distribution of the commodities which they produce.\nLooking at the picture today in this light, it is quite appar\nent that Congress is the target at which labor must aim its pres\nsure, and which it must convince that it not only means busi\nness, but that it has the power to detroy the political life of those\nwho refuse to go along with labor\u2019s program of full employment.\nThis brings us to the question\u2014can labor destroy on the po\nlitical field those who stand in the way of its realization of\ngreater security through a full employment program? In all\nfrankness, we must give a yes and no answer, for today, labor\nstill is unable to control the southern Democrats, and apparently\nis not sufficiently educated to rid itself of many of the reaction\nary northern Republicans.\nlhe crisis is not here yet, but we arc rapidly approaching\nit. Labor\u2019s educational program has barely scratched the sur\nface. Meanwhile, industry is opposing any legislation to give\nI full employment, because it regards labor not as human beings,\nbut as a marketable commodity.\n3\na\nEditor\u2019s Mail\nRegistration Contrasts\nDear Sir:\nIn a survey of the registra\ntion of citizens of Lucas Coun\nty, we find that less than 50%\nhave registered to vote. Labor\nregistration is less than 50%.\nOn the other hand, we find\nthat the employing class have\nregistered 100%, We find in\nthis class husband, wife and\nchildren all registered which\ngives them the jump on elec\ntions. Such being the case,\nthey take those elected under\ntheir wings and point the way,\nwhen and how.\nIf Labor would register\n100% and vote, they would\nnot have to point the way,\nWhen and how. Those elected\nto the General Assembly\nWould know the strength of\nthe common man and would\nset accordingly. It is up to\nthe plain people to organize\n100%, register and vote and\nshow the money-grabbers and\ntheir friends that we know\nhow and why. We want a voice\ntn our government that is why\ncommon men in Lucas County\nshould organize under the\nPAC and try to educate those\nWho have that feeling.\nWe are going to show them\nhow they are leaving* the\nmoney-grabbers have their\nway to the detriment of the\ncommon man. This General\nAssembly has done a great\njob for the greedy but noth\ning for the needy. That being\nthe case, it is time to leave\nthem to the mercy of their\nfriends, the money-grabbers,\nwhom they have so nobly sup\nported and retire them to their\ndifferent vocations lawyers,\npreachers, publishers and\nwhat have you.\nThe way they have treated\nthe aged is a disgrace to the\nState of Ohio. They have left\nthem the great sum $29.30\nper month. There is one allot\nment which is exorbitant and\nthat is the medical attention\u2014\n$12 per year. Think of that!\nLet us join in one united ef\nfort and show the politicians\nthat we have taken our first\nstep toward retirement for\nthem and put men and women\ninto office who will live up to\ntheir promises. Let us demand\na signed resignation by those\nrunning so we do not have\nto wait two years to get rid\nof them. We do not care to\nwhat party they belong, for\nwe will support the person,\nApt the party.\nYours, truly.\nH. J. Robedeau, Pre*\nOhio Old Age Society\nof Lucas County\nRR #3 Box 34k A\nToledo 7, Ohio.'\nThe National Association of\nManufacturers is threatening\na sitdown strike unless OPA\nlifts price ceilings. War\nmanufacturers, sitting on a\n$28 billion dollar tax rebate\nfrom Federal Treasury, feel\nthey can afford to refuse to\nplay ball. OPA, with the\njobless worker in mind and\nwith fear of inflation, is\nanxious to hold do^n prices.\nThe battle line-up, OPA vs.\nNAM.\nC. I. O. has donated $55,\n000 to the new Georgetowl\nHospital, Washington, D. C.,\nfor a children's wing honor\ning the memory of late Presi\ndent oosevelt. In making the\ndonation, C. I. O. President\nPhilip Murray said, \"We can\nconceive of no better method\nof paying tribute to our late\nPresident than the best of\nmedical care for little chil\ndren.\u201d\n\"If we cannot give the\nvoters of this country reason\nably steady employment at\ndecent wages, we are wasting\nour breath in talking about\nthe glories of the free enter\nprise system because they are\nbound to vote for a change\nto another system, just as the\nvoters in England did a few\nweeks ago.\u201d\n\u2014Clarence Avildsen,\nChicago businessman.\nWashington\nCt\nLaborReport\nBy Bradford V. Carter\nLPA Columnist\nSABOTAGE\nThis much is clear the\nfull impact of the V-J cut\nbacks has not yet been felt.\nBut the way in which Wash\nington is dismantling its war\ntime agencies suggests that\noutfits like the War Produc\ntion Board, Office of Price\nAdministration and the War\nLabor Board are not going to\nstick around long enough to\nfind out if they will be need\ned for the transition. Mean\nwhile, on Capital Hill, liberal\nand labor spokesmen are put\nting their full weight behind\nthe Murray Full Employment\nbill, and more.\nIn the opinion of competent\nobservers in and out of gov\nernment, the spirit of Presi\ndent Truman\u2019s executive or\nder in which he set forth the\nguiding principles for theT\ngovernment\u2019s positive role in\nreconversion, is being vio\nlated. The War Production\nBoard, for example, is cutting\nits staffs drastically and thou\nsands of notices of layoffs to\ntake effect the end of this\nmonth are being sent out.\nThis means that if, and when,\nproduction bottlenecks do de\nvelop, there will be nobody\naround to do anything about\nthem.\nWPB BREAKUP\nSOMETHING NEW\nIn other words, WPB\nChairman Krug is taking the\nbit in his teeth and settling\nthe question of WPB\u2019s partici\npation in reconversion by\nbreaking up the WPB. The\nWar Labor Board is suddenly\ngetting skittish, and is turn\ning cases back to Labor De\npartment\u2019s Conciliation Serv\nice.\nThe disposition of the erst\nwhile war agencies to default\non their reconversion respon\nsibilities, fits perfectly into\nwhat appears to be the grand\nstrategy of business. Thor\nstein Veblen, an economist\nwith a flair for words, once\ndescribed sabotage as a \u201ccon\nscientious withdrawal of effi\nciency.\u201d\nIt appears now as if busi\nness is engaging in a \u201cconsci\nentious withdrawal of effi\nciency\u201d until it gets what it\nconsiders to be price \u201crelief.\u201d\nIn industry after industry the\ntheme song is \"we want price\nrelief and we won\u2019t produce\nuntil we get it.\" This refrain\nis echoed by the industry peo\nple in government.\nSomething new has been\nadded to the discussion on\nCapital Hill of the Murray\nFull Employment Bill. The.\ngeneral idea which labor and\nliberal groups have been ex\npounding before the Senate\nBanking and Currency Com\nmittee, chaired by Senator\nWagner, is that they are in\nfull accord with the Full em\nployment Bill., But now im\nplementation of the bill is be\ning called for.\nWhat the Senate committee\nis being told amounts to\nsomething like this: \u201cYes, the\nMurray Full Employment bill\ndoes commit the government\nto a responsibility for pro\nmoting and maintaining full\nemployment. The mere com\nmitment alone, however, will\nnot provide full employment.\nWe need to enact concrete\nmeasures which will do the\njob.\u201d\nLabor also feels that the\nbill as presently written is\nsomewhat on the defensive in\ncommitting the government\nto full employment. There are\nrestrictions and limitations\nwhich could conceivably im\npede the speedy fulfillment of\nthe government\u2019s responsibil\nity for full employment.\nThere is strong indieatfbrt\nthat tiie Senate Committee,\nheaded by Senator Wagner,\nwill take the bill back to the\ncommittee and revise it in ac\ncord with many of the recom\nmendations which labor is ad\nvancing.\nHere, then, is the way the\nsituation sizes up in terms of\n\u201cwhat next.\u201d For the short\nrun, labor and this means\nlocal unions and individual\nmembers will need to be\nalert to impediments to full\nemployment and full produc\ntion. They will need to\nsquawk loudly, where it will\ndo the most good, and when\never these blocks develop.\nFor the longer pull, progres\nsive forces will have to mo\nbilize all of their strength to\nget positive legislation for full\nemployment if they want to\navoid a brush-off.\nIn favoring a stronger Full\nEmployment Bill, Mr. F. R.\nVon Windegger, St. Louis\nbanker, had this to say about\nhis fellow bankers who have\nfought the bill: \u201cI have con\ncluded that the chief quality\nto be head of a bank is a con\nstitutional inability to grasp a\nnew idea,*\nRegional\nViews\nBy Richard Qosser\nFriday, September 7, 194S\nI\nDirector Report-2B, UAW'-CIO\nThis is being written before any of us know\nwhat the outcome of the special session of the\nstate legislature called by Governor Lausche\nfor Sept. 5 will be. 1 have no way of knowing\nwhat will result from our efforts to induce the\nlegislators to make the new unemployment\ncompensation bill an emergency measure ef\nfective at once.\nIn a matter as serious as the living and\nlives of thousands of Ohio\u2019s unemployed, we\nare hopeful that this question will be taken\nout of its political implications and considered\nas a question involving the welfare of the citi\nzens of Ohio, the same as though it were a dis\nastrous flood, fire or other emergency.\nIf there are political implications, it will be\nbecause some of the politicians want them. If\nthe state legislature, because of its large num\nber of Republican members decides to use the\noccasion to shove around the Democratic gov\npernor of the state, it will mean a worse shov\ning around for those who are in dire need of\nincreased unemployment benefits.\nNO ASSURANCES\nNone of the labor people in Ohio have any\nway of knowing beforehand what will occur\nwhen the legislature meets this week. We only\nknow that the bill has already been passed,\nEffective October 12, and that most of the un\nemployed cannot wait until that date to apply\nfor their unemployment insurance. Many of\nthose who have not yet made application have\nheld off with great difficulty this long in the\nhope that favorable action would be taken and\ntheir benefits increased by $5.00 a week and\nthe time increased from 18 to 22 weeks.\nWe are not asking for anything unreason\nable. The law increasing unemployment com\npensation has been passed, but was not made\nan emergency measure probably because the\nmembers of the state legislature had no more\nWay of knowing than we did that the war with\nJapan would end so quickly.\nWe are merely asking the legislature to\n\u25a0nove the effective date for drawing the in\ncreased compensation up to the point where\nthe people can get it when they need it the\nmost\u2014now.\nThe thousands of dollars of additional com\npensation which will go into the hands of the\nunemployed who need and want the higher\nbenefits right now will reflect itself in in\ncreased benefits to every retail merchant in\nthe state of Ohio. It will act as a primer for\nthe pump by creating additional purchasing\npower at a time when it is needed and speed\nthe reconversion and full production upon\nwhich the prosperity of this state and nation\ndepend.\nFrom The Desk\nof\nMelvin Schultz\nPresident,\nLocal\n12,\nUAW-CIO\n.\u2019J\nLabor Day of 1945 has just been celebrated\nand is the first Labor Day in five years cele\nbrated without the cloud of war hanging over\nlabor\u2019s head. In looking backwards the past\nfour years, we find that labor in general has\ndone a very good job in producing all of the\nmaterials needed for the preservation of the\ncountry which we consider the best in the\nworld.\nI think it is good to observe that the Sec\nretary of Labor of the United States has found\nthat work stoppages during the war were few\nand far between and added all together would\nnot amount to much more than two hours for\neach worker in our country. Considering Man\nagement\u2019s reluctance to enter into the war ef\nfort and the resistance which was put up frora\ntime to time against the efforts of O. P. A., we\ncan with pride claim to have put forth the big\ngest share of the effort which lias won World\nWar II.\nWe may have condemned the War Labor\nBoard, Wage Stabilization, and many of the\npeople involved in the execution of the Ex\necutive Orders whidh were followed during\nthe war however, I think it goes without say\ning that laboring people in our country would\nbe well off and should be contented if during\nthe next five years they were to be provided\nwith at least an equivalent amount of jobs and\nwork with equivalent economic conditions to\nthose which existed during the war. Wc, of\ncourse, do not want the war or the wartime\narmed forces. This would, of course, mean\nthat jobs must then be provided for the men\nand women who are released from the armed\nforces. It is simple arithmetic to say that this\ncan be accomplished by reducing the work\nweek to no more than forty hours per week\ngiving everybody the equivalent in pay which\nthey drew during the war or a fifty-two hour\npay check for forty hours of work. Cutting\ndown the working hours provides the extra\njobs necessary and increasing the pay balances\nthe economic condition.\nSubstituting new automobiles, refrigerai\ntors, washers, irons, radios, style changes and\nnew models for war materials will provide\nthe jobs to take the place of the wartime jobs.\nThe above does not quite complete the pro\ngram which would make the country even\nbetter than the one for which the armed forces\ngave their lives. We need a national program\nenacted into law giving cradle to the grave\nsecurity because during the best of times there\nare those people who meet with misfortune\nand need the assistance of the balance of\nsociety. Workers who have given many years\nof their lives on the production front should be\ngiven the opportunity of retirement in se\ncurity. This, of course, means not only their\ndaily living necessities, but also recreational\nfacilities for the enjoyment of the remainder\nof their lives.\nYes, the goal of organized labor is still a\nconsiderable way off and it requires study and\nunderstanding of this goal by all members of\norganized labor to understand the reasons ioc\ncontinuing our organizational efforts.","height":"26904","width":"20370"}}
